<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-02-24T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-02-24T11:00:00-05:00" n="932" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d932">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/2884a.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">American
                                    Ambassador</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Paraphrase.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-02-24T11:00:00-05:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">February 24, 1912—11 a.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>The President feels that his duty and public opinion absolutely forbid
                            toleration of any repetition of injury to Americans on American soil, as
                            now threatened at Juárez, and he is disposed to give <pb facs="0841" n="725" xml:id="pg_725"/> public warning that in such emergency he
                            would be obliged to order troops to cross the line, as a police measure,
                            and to disarm or drive away from Juárez any fighting forces threatening
                            life in El Paso, thereafter returning.</p>
                        <p>Inform the Department of your judgment in reference to the proposed
                            action for the safety of Americans in Mexico generally, and also your
                            judgment whether or not to advise them to withdraw at this time.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>